{
  "card_id": "london_reversal",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "London Reversal",
  "aliases": [
    "2 a.m. reversal",
    "4-hour C2 closure",
    "4-hour c2 closure",
    "Bearish Classic Expansion",
    "bearish classic expansion",
    "Bullish Classic Expansion",
    "bullish classic expansion",
    "classic expansion candle",
    "Classic Expansion Candle",
    "london reversal new york continuation",
    "London Reversal New York Continuation",
    "London Reversal Profile",
    "london reversal profile",
    "伦敦反转"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A daily profile where the London session (02:00–05:00 ET) sweeps a higher time frame level or liquidity, then reverses with a Change in the State of Delivery (CISD/MSS), forming the daily candle's wick. The New York session continues in the reversal direction, completing the daily candle as Open-Low-High-Close (bullish) or Open-High-Low-Close (bearish).",
  "identification_rules": [
    "During the London Kill Zone (02:00–05:00 ET), price sweeps a liquidity level (swing high/low) or reaches a higher-time-frame PD Array.",
    "A Change in the State of Delivery (CISD) is confirmed by price closing through the opposing candle series that formed the London swing, creating a precision/protected swing point.",
    "A 4-hour candle 2 closure often occurs, sweeping the prior candle's extreme and closing back inside its range, confirming the reversal.",
    "The reversal is ideally confirmed by a cracking correlation SMT against a correlated asset.",
    "The London move forms the wick of the daily candle; the body and close are not yet established during London.",
    "During the New York session (08:30–12:00 ET), price continues in the direction of London's reversal rather than extending London's initial sweep direction.",
    "Key New York time levels (08:30, 09:30, 10:00) are monitored for manipulation runs or continuation entries aligned with the London reversal direction.",
    "The daily candle closes in the direction of the New York continuation, completing the Open-Low-High-Close (bullish) or Open-High-Low-Close (bearish) structure."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Once London confirms a CISD, traders wait for New York session (around 09:30 ET) to enter in the reversal direction on lower time frames, using London order blocks or propulsion blocks as entries, with stops beyond the London swing. Targets include previous day high/low, opposing daily range extreme, fair value gaps, or daily equilibrium. New York manipulation moves at 08:30 or 09:30 against the reversal direction are treated as entry opportunities rather than invalidations.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering during London session before the CISD is confirmed, risking being caught in the manipulation sweep rather than the reversal.",
    "Calling a London reversal without confirming a change in state of delivery (close through opposing candle series).",
    "Confusing a London Reversal with other daily profiles (e.g., New York Reversal) when London's move does not produce a clear CISD.",
    "Misidentifying the profile when New York does not immediately continue in the reversal direction at 08:30 — an opposing manipulation move at 08:30 or 09:30 is normal and should be used as an entry, not treated as invalidation.",
    "Targeting an intermediate low/high when the actual higher time frame draw on liquidity is further away.",
    "Taking the reversal without confirming with an SMT/cracking correlation and precision swing point.",
    "Confusing a continuation profile with a reversal — expecting a manipulation of the previous day high/low instead of expansion through it.",
    "Misreading shallow moves against the trend as reversals; these are often retracements supporting continuation.",
    "Misreading New York initial manipulation as immediate entry without allowing for liquidity engineering."
  ],
